Unless you're going to argue that Righetti used to be good and isn't any
more, then that's the wrong question.  A better question, IMO, is
whether you would have taken their careers so far if you were asked on
the day they were called up (or brought in from elsewhere).  I think
with Cain and Lincecum the answer has to be yes, and with Lowry it's a
huge yes.  The only current pitcher who I think would be the other way
would be Zito.  I mean, did anyone expect Hennessey to be a lights out
closer?

Looking back, and figuring that the pitching coach is more responsible
for young pitchers than established guys, I think the only two flameouts
(at the major league level) in recent years were Foppert, which was an
injury thing (and not an injury because of misuse in the majors; it must
have happened before), and Jerome Williams.  So you can blame the
pitching coach in that case if you want, although it must count for
something that no one else could get Jerome straightened out, either.

I don't think coaches are very important, at any rate, but it's hard to
see how he's to blame for anything.

